Bonanza Creek Snowshoe Hares: Exploratory Report

Anastasia Kunz

11/16/2020

Anastasia Kunz

1. Overview

This report explores analysis of population dynamics of an important keystone species, the Snowshoe hare(Lepus americanus) in central Alaska at Bonanza Creek Long Term Ecological Research (LTER). Specifically, this capture-recapture study looked to monitor the 8-11yr population fluctuations through different(3????) trap locations and physical specimen metrics including sex, weight, age, and hindfoot length. Relationships between hare sex, weight and hindfoot length is explored in this study.Bonanza Creek includes multiple specific habitat types including riparian, black spruce and mature forest.

2. Data and Analysis

Senior Investigator Knut Kielland as well as Primary Investigators Stuart Chapin and Roger Ruess collected and authored the Snowshoe hare dataset through the Bonanza Creek LTER1. The snowshoe hare data used in this analysis includes information about the trap location and ID, as well as individual metrics about the observed specimen including weight, sex, age, and hindfoot length through capture-recapture trapping. Preliminary analysis explores visualization of total hare populations per year. Next, this analysis depicts hare counts by sex at each of three trapping sites; riparian boreal forest, black spruce boreal forest, and mature boreal forest. After these preliminary population visualizations, this report explores basic sample population statistics as well as analysis of Cohens d effect size and a two sample t-test comparing difference in means using a significance level (\(\alpha\)). Next this analysis displays the relationship between juvenile hare weight and hindfoot length through a simple linear regression. All analyses are in R version 4.0.2 using RStudio version 1.3.1073.

3. Exploratory Findings

A. Annual Juvenile Hare Trap Counts

In 1999 we see the most juvenile hares trapped with a maximum count of 126 juvenile hares. However in two years, 2002 and 2009, there was a minimum count value where no juvenile hares were observed. The trend in Figure 1. shows a steep overall decline in juvenile hare populations, with semi-consistent yearly fluctuations. It is important to note the consistency of days each year that hares were recorded. In some years there are significantly more days in which data is recorded than in other years. For example, only 19 observations were recorded in 2002 with only 3 observations including age. Similarly, age of the hares is inconsistently reported, so it is difficult to comment on population trends without age assessment of the hares that were trapped. In addition, duplicate individuals were recorded both between traps as well as observation duplication. For better total count analysis, there should be consistency in the number of trapping days and number of traps set.

Figure 1. Total juvenile hares recorded per year at all trapping sites in Bonanza Creek, Alaska. The 1999 had a maximum hare count of 126, while both 2002 and 2009 had 0 juvenile hare observations. There is an overall decrease in juvenile hare counts for this study period. Data: Kielland et al.2017.

B. Visualize Juvenille Hare Weights

In Figure 2, visualization of female and male juvenile hare weights show that for the riparian and mature Bonanza trapping locations, the male juvenile hares have a greater weight than females. However in the black spruce trapping location, differences in male and female juvenile hare weight is much smaller than in the other two trapping locations. It is important to note that in the riparian trapping area, there are also hares trapped with no sex recorded that have a much smaller weight than either the recorded males or females.

Figure 2. Box and whisker plot showing weight(g) of juvenile female, male, and NA Snowshoe hares in Bonanza Creek, Alaska. Plots are separated out by trapping site at Bonanza Black Spruce, Bonanza Riparian, or Bonanza Mature locations. Data: Kielland et al.2017.

C. Juvenile Weight Comparison (Male & Female)

Table 1. Descriptive statistics (mean, standard deviation, and sample size) comparing juvenile male and female Snowshoe hares. Data: Kielland et al.2017.
Sex Mean Weight (g) Standard Deviation (g) Sample Size
Female 855.3909 292.2526 200
Male 945.8589 333.2151 163

Juvenile hare mean weight (g) were compared between male and female hares. This statistical analysis shows that when comparing mean juvenile hare weight, males (945.86g, n = 163) were larger than females (855.39g, n = 200) with an actual difference in means of 90.47g. This shows a a 10.05% difference (Table 1). Statistical analysis using a two sample t-test showed this difference to be significant (Welches Two Sample T-Test: t(2.71) p = 0.01), with a small effect size (Cohens d = 0.29).

D. Relationship Between Juvenile Weight and Hind Foot Length

Figure 3 explores the relationship between juvenile hare weight and hindfoot length. Using a simple linear regression, we see that hindfoot lenghth very roughly predicts hare weight (p < 0.001, R2 = 0.3) with an average slope of \(\beta\)1 = 0.03g mm-1. We find that the correlation is not very strong (Pearsons r = 0.55) and overall hindfoot length is not an adequate descriptor of hare weight.

Figure 3. Relationship between weight(g) and hindfoot length (mm) for juvenile hares in Bonanza Creek, Alaska. Each point indicates a juvenile hare observation from 1999 - 2012. Linear model summary: 0.03g mm-1, R2 = 0.3, Pearsons r = 0.55. Data: Kielland et al.2017.
